The paper deals with communication schemes and their optimality over memoryless channels, which are topics typically studied in the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of randomization and analysis of random walks, which are techniques commonly used in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. The paper's focus on analyzing the behavior of posterior intervals also suggests a possible fit in the Information Theory and Probability (cs.ITP) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of a reversed iterated function system (RIFS) decoder suggests a possible fit in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
